  "prompt": "What universities does Immune Design recruit new grads from? What majors are they looking for?",
  "response": "As of my knowledge up to October 2023, **Immune Design** is a biotechnology company focused on developing immunotherapies for cancer and other diseases. While specific details about their recruiting practices might not be publicly detailed, biotech companies like Immune Design typically seek fresh graduates from a range of reputable universities and diverse academic backgrounds relevant to their field.\n\n### **Universities**\nImmune Design likely targets universities known for strong programs in the life sciences, biotechnology, and related fields. While there isn't a publicly available list of specific universities they recruit from, candidates from the following types of institutions may find opportunities:\n\n- **Top Research Universities:** Institutions like **Johns Hopkins University**, **Massachusetts Institute of Technology (MIT)**, **Stanford University**, **University of California, Berkeley**, and **Harvard University** are renowned for their robust biotech and life sciences programs.\n  \n- **Strong Regional Universities:** Schools with strong regional biotech programs such as **University of Wisconsin-Madison**, **North Carolina State University**, **University of Texas at Austin**, and **Purdue University** often have graduates well-prepared for roles in biotech firms.\n\n- **Specialized Institutes:** Institutions like the **Scripps Research Institute**, **Rockefeller University**, and similar centers focus intensively on biomedical research and may be key sources of talent.\n\n### **Majors and Academic Backgrounds**\nImmune Design typically looks for candidates with educational backgrounds that align with their research and development needs. Relevant majors and fields of study may include:\n\n- **Immunology:** Directly relevant to their focus on immunotherapies.\n- **Biotechnology:** Provides a foundation in the technologies used in developing therapies.\n- **Molecular Biology & Genetics:** Essential for understanding the molecular mechanisms of diseases and treatments.\n- **Biochemistry:** Important for the chemical processes and substances within living organisms.\n- **Pharmaceutical Sciences:** Relevant for drug development and regulatory aspects.\n- **Biomedical Engineering:** Combines engineering principles with medical and biological sciences.\n- **Chemistry:** Particularly medicinal chemistry, which is vital in drug design and development.\n- **Bioinformatics & Computational Biology:** Increasingly important for data analysis and managing biological data.\n- **Cell Biology:** Essential for understanding cell function and development of cell-based therapies.\n\n### **Additional Considerations**\nBeyond academic majors, Immune Design and similar companies often seek candidates with:\n\n- **Research Experience:** Hands-on laboratory experience, internships, or research projects.\n- **Technical Skills:** Proficiency in relevant laboratory techniques, data analysis software, or bioinformatics tools.\n- **Soft Skills:** Strong communication, problem-solving abilities, and teamwork.\n- **Advanced Degrees:** While not always required, candidates with master's degrees or PhDs may have an advantage for more specialized roles.\n\n### **Recommendations for Prospective Candidates**\n1. **Check the Official Website:** Visit Immune Design\u2019s [Careers Page](https://www.immunedesign.com/careers/) (if available) for specific job postings and requirements.\n2. **Reach Out Directly:** Contact their HR department or recruiters for detailed information about recruitment preferences.\n3. **Attend Career Fairs:** Engage with company representatives at biotech and pharmaceutical industry career fairs.\n4. **Leverage University Resources:** Utilize your university\u2019s career services and alumni network to connect with employees at Immune Design.\n5. **Stay Updated on Job Platforms:** Regularly monitor job boards like LinkedIn, Indeed, and Glassdoor for openings and company insights.\n\nBy aligning your educational background and experiences with the needs of Immune Design, you can enhance your prospects of securing a position with them or similar biotech companies.",
